{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/run/current-system/sw/bin/bash -lc \"nl -ba packages/app/src/client/App.tsx | sed -n '548,620p;780,830p'; nl -ba packages/common/src/alerts.ts | sed -n '100,122p'; nl -ba packages/agent/src/main.ts | sed -n '185,208p;314,330p'; git status --short\"","aggregated_output":"   548\t  // ── Cross-host attention (kolu W5: watchByEntry + notify) ──────────────\n   549\t  // The FRAMEWORK-GATE consumer of the new `alerts` cell: watch EVERY host's\n   550\t  // alerts EAGERLY (a background host in trouble is exactly the one you need to\n   551\t  // hear from) and fire an OS notification per newly-raised metric. Raise\n   552\t  // detection is the framework's pure set-diff over the stable alert ids; this\n   553\t  // runs under `MultiHostApp`'s reactive owner (watchByEntry throws otherwise)\n   554\t  // and every per-host subscription tears down when the host leaves the fleet.\n   555\t  // Permission is requested once (idempotent); delivery is a silent no-op until\n   556\t  // granted, so an un-permissioned browser costs nothing. The request MUST ride\n   557\t  // a real user gesture: Firefox and Safari SUPPRESS a bare init-time\n   558\t  // `requestPermission()` (the prompt never shows) unless it fires from user\n   559\t  // activation, so asking eagerly here would leave first-time users on those\n   560\t  // browsers with alerts silently off. Ask on the first pointer/key interaction\n   561\t  // instead — a one-shot listener that removes itself (and its siblings) the\n   562\t  // instant either fires, so exactly one prompt is raised and none leaks past\n   563\t  // teardown. `requestPermission` is idempotent (resolves immediately, no\n   564\t  // prompt, once already granted/denied) and a no-op on an unsupported browser.\n   565\t  const requestNotifyPermission = () => {\n   566\t    window.removeEventListener(\"pointerdown\", requestNotifyPermission, true);\n   567\t    window.removeEventListener(\"keydown\", requestNotifyPermission, true);\n   568\t    void notify.requestPermission();\n   569\t  };\n   570\t  window.addEventListener(\"pointerdown\", requestNotifyPermission, true);\n   571\t  window.addEventListener(\"keydown\", requestNotifyPermission, true);\n   572\t  onCleanup(() => {\n   573\t    window.removeEventListener(\"pointerdown\", requestNotifyPermission, true);\n   574\t    window.removeEventListener(\"keydown\", requestNotifyPermission, true);\n   575\t  });\n   576\t  const alertsWatch = watchByEntry(\n   577\t    hostMap,\n   578\t    (e) => e.cells.alerts,\n   579\t    (v) => v.items,\n   580\t    (host, raised) =>\n   581\t      raised.forEach((id) =>\n   582\t        void notify.show({\n   583\t          tag: `${host}/${id}`,\n   584\t          title: `${host}: ${LABELS[id]} alert`,\n   585\t          data: { host, id },\n   586\t        }),\n   587\t      ),\n   588\t  );\n   589\t  // A notification click drills into the host it fired for — drishti's\n   590\t  // host-select is just setting the `view` intent. Torn down with the app.\n   591\t  onCleanup(notify.onClick(({ host }) => setView({ kind: \"host\", host })));\n   592\t\n   593\t  // App badge = the COUNT OF HOSTS with any LIVE alert (drishti's own fold — a\n   594\t  // host in trouble is one unit of attention, NOT the sum of its raised\n   595\t  // metrics). A stale host (its link down) keeps its last value marked stale\n   596\t  // and is deliberately NOT counted — a badge should reflect what's live. Guard\n   597\t  // the Badging API (absent on some browsers) at the call site.\n   598\t  createEffect(() => {\n   599\t    const count = hostList().reduce((n, host) => {\n   600\t      const w = alertsWatch.get(host);\n   601\t      return n + (w?.kind === \"live\" && w.value.items.length > 0 ? 1 : 0);\n   602\t    }, 0);\n   603\t    if (typeof navigator === \"undefined\") return;\n   604\t    const nav = navigator as BadgingNavigator;\n   605\t    // The Badging API can REJECT even when present (permission, security, or\n   606\t    // document-state failures), and `void` discards only the value, not a\n   607\t    // rejection — so swallow-and-log here, or a fire-and-forget badge update\n   608\t    // becomes an unhandled promise rejection every time this effect runs.\n   609\t    const badgeOp = count > 0 ? nav.setAppBadge?.(count) : nav.clearAppBadge?.();\n   610\t    void badgeOp?.catch((err: unknown) =>\n   611\t      console.warn(\"app badge update failed\", err),\n   612\t    );\n   613\t  });\n   614\t\n   615\t  // Theme is global app chrome (like `view`), so it lives here, not per\n   616\t  // host. The signal seeds from the attribute the pre-paint bootstrap in\n   617\t  // index.html already applied; toggling flips the attribute and persists\n   618\t  // the choice. `applyTheme` is the single writer of both DOM and storage.\n   619\t  const [theme, setTheme] = createSignal<Theme>(initialTheme());\n   620\t  // The signal is the source of truth; this effect projects it to the DOM\n   780\t  const connection = entry.cells.connection.use({});\n   781\t  // The host's raised-alert set (kolu W5 `alerts` cell). A minimal pip on the\n   782\t  // card surfaces \"this host is in trouble\" at a glance, alongside the OS\n   783\t  // notification the app-scope `watchByEntry` fires — same source of truth. The\n   784\t  // pip is gated on a LIVE connection (below) so a disconnected host's stale\n   785\t  // last-known set isn't painted as a live alert — the same live-only policy the\n   786\t  // app badge applies, and consistent with the metrics body's disconnect gate.\n   787\t  const alerts = entry.cells.alerts.use({});\n   788\t  const alertCount = createMemo(() => alerts.value()?.items.length ?? 0);\n   789\t\n   790\t  const sys = createMemo<SystemInfo>(() => system.value() ?? DEFAULT_SYSTEM);\n   791\t  const state = createMemo<ConnectionState>(\n   792\t    () => (connection.value() ?? DEFAULT_CONNECTION).phase,\n   793\t  );\n   794\t  // The dot + readiness gate read the host MAP's `EntryStatus` fact\n   795\t  // (floored on real transport liveness by `connectSurfaceMap`) — the\n   796\t  // per-host `SurfaceHealth`/`app.health()` this used to gate on no longer\n   797\t  // exists now that every host rides the ONE admin transport. The status\n   798\t  // WORD stays driven by the richer `ConnectionState` cell (copying vs\n   799\t  // connecting vs the failure detail) — see `HostDot.tsx`'s docstring for\n   800\t  // why the dot and the word now read two different facts.\n   801\t  const entryState = createMemo<EntryState>(() => entry.state());\n   802\t  // CPU% and the core count are read straight off the `system` cell — the agent\n   803\t  // folds them in (`system.cpuPct` / `system.coreCount`). The card used to open\n   804\t  // the per-key `cpuCores` collection (one value stream PER core PER host) just\n   805\t  // to average it for one number; reading the aggregate cell drops the fleet's\n   806\t  // entire O(hosts×cores) subscription fan-out. The per-core collection stays\n   807\t  // for the host drill-in (CpuStrip), which actually renders a bar per core.\n   808\t  const cpuPct = createMemo(() => sys().cpuPct);\n   809\t  const coreCount = createMemo(() => sys().coreCount);\n   810\t  const mem = createMemo(() => memPct(sys()));\n   811\t  const memText = createMemo(() => {\n   812\t    const gb = memGb(sys());\n   813\t    return `${gb.used}/${gb.total} GB · ${mem().toFixed(0)}%`;\n   814\t  });\n   815\t  const disk = createMemo(() => diskPct(sys()));\n   816\t  const diskText = createMemo(() => {\n   817\t    const gb = diskGb(sys());\n   818\t    return `/ · ${gb.used}/${gb.total} GB · ${disk().toFixed(0)}%`;\n   819\t  });\n   820\t\n   821\t  return (\n   822\t    <button\n   823\t      type=\"button\"\n   824\t      onClick={props.onSelect}\n   825\t      class=\"flex flex-col gap-2 rounded border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 p-3 text-left transition-colors hover:border-indigo-400 hover:bg-white dark:border-gray-800 dark:bg-gray-900/40 dark:hover:border-indigo-500 dark:hover:bg-gray-900\"\n   826\t    >\n   827\t      <div class=\"flex items-center gap-2\">\n   828\t        <HostDot state={entryState} class=\"shrink-0\" />\n   829\t        <span class=\"truncate font-semibold\" title={props.host}>\n   830\t          {props.host}\n   100\t  // regardless of raise sequence.\n   101\t  return { items: METRIC_IDS.filter((id) => raised.has(id)) };\n   102\t}\n   103\t\n   104\t/** Equal iff the SAME set of alert ids is raised — the cell's `equals` gate.\n   105\t *  Only a raise or a clear (a change to the id set) crosses the wire. Compares\n   106\t *  as true sets (size + membership) so it stays honest even if a caller ever\n   107\t *  hands in a non-canonical list with a repeat — the fold only ever emits the\n   108\t *  unique, order-stable `METRIC_IDS.filter(...)` result, but the exported\n   109\t *  predicate should not silently mistake `[\"cpu\",\"cpu\"]` for `[\"cpu\",\"mem\"]`. */\n   110\texport function alertsEqual(a: Alerts, b: Alerts): boolean {\n   111\t  const as = new Set(a.items);\n   112\t  const bs = new Set(b.items);\n   113\t  if (as.size !== bs.size) return false;\n   114\t  for (const id of as) if (!bs.has(id)) return false;\n   115\t  return true;\n   116\t}\n   185\t  const snapshotDeltaBus = inMemoryChannel<ProcessesSnapshotMsg>();\n   186\t\n   187\t  // The metrics SOURCE feeding the `alerts` reactor graph. The poll `tick`\n   188\t  // pushes one `MetricsFrame` per tick through `emitMetrics`; `scan` folds each\n   189\t  // occurrence into the raised-alert set via the pure `applyHysteresis`, and\n   190\t  // `derived.cell` publishes that level as the wire-read-only `alerts` cell (its\n   191\t  // own `equals` gate, `alertsEqual`, is the wire dedup). No store: `alerts`\n   192\t  // must NOT survive a restart — a fresh process re-derives its level from fresh\n   193\t  // samples. `emitMetrics` is installed SYNCHRONOUSLY the moment `scan(metrics,\n   194\t  // …)` below subscribes to this source — that happens while the `cells` literal\n   195\t  // is evaluated to build `implementSurface`'s argument, BEFORE the runtime ever\n   196\t  // fires the `derived.cell` connect effect. It goes null again only when that\n   197\t  // scan/source subscription tears down at dispose. So the poll's `?.` guard\n   198\t  // covers the pre-construction / post-teardown window, not a pre-connect gap.\n   199\t  let emitMetrics: ((f: MetricsFrame) => void) | null = null;\n   200\t  const metrics = source<MetricsFrame>((emit) => {\n   201\t    emitMetrics = emit;\n   202\t    return () => {\n   203\t      emitMetrics = null;\n   204\t    };\n   205\t  });\n   206\t\n   207\t  const fragment = implementSurface(surface, {\n   208\t    channel: inMemoryChannelByName(),\n   314\t      const sys = {\n   315\t        ...nextSystem,\n   316\t        ...cpuAggregate(nextCores),\n   317\t        pollIntervalMs: POLL_INTERVAL_MS,\n   318\t      };\n   319\t      fragment.ctx.cells.system.set(sys);\n   320\t      // Feed the alert reactor the frame just composed. `emitMetrics` was\n   321\t      // installed synchronously when `scan` subscribed to the source at\n   322\t      // construction (see above), so by the time this poll runs it is already\n   323\t      // live; it is null only after the scan/source subscription tears down at\n   324\t      // dispose, where the `?.` makes a late tick a harmless no-op.\n   325\t      emitMetrics?.(metricPercents(sys));\n   326\t      const upserts: Array<[Pid, Process]> = [];\n   327\t      const removes: Pid[] = [];\n   328\t      for (const [pid, value] of nextProcesses) {\n   329\t        const prev = processSnapshot.get(pid);\n   330\t        if (prev === undefined || processChanged(prev, value)) {\n?? .codex-debate/codex-session.id\n?? .codex-debate/rationale.md\n?? .codex-debate/section-001-1-codex.md\n?? .codex-debate/verdict-1.json\n?? .codex-debate/verdict-1.json.log\n?? .codex-debate/verdict-2.json.log\n?? .lens-debate/\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"agent_message","text":"{\"approved\":true,\"summary\":\"All five findings are resolved. The fixes correctly move notification permission into a one-shot user gesture, contain badge promise rejections, hide stale card alerts, implement true set equality, and correct the reactor lifecycle documentation. Full typechecking passes, and the 34 targeted tests pass.\",\"findings\":[{\"id\":\"F1\",\"severity\":\"major\",\"location\":\"packages/app/src/client/App.tsx:565\",\"issue\":\"The notification permission request now runs synchronously from the first pointer or keyboard gesture, with both listeners removed immediately and again during cleanup.\",\"suggestion\":\"No further change required.\",\"status\":\"resolved\"},{\"id\":\"F2\",\"severity\":\"minor\",\"location\":\"packages/app/src/client/App.tsx:609\",\"issue\":\"Both badge operations now route rejected promises to a warning instead of causing unhandled rejections.\",\"suggestion\":\"No further change required.\",\"status\":\"resolved\"},{\"id\":\"F3\",\"severity\":\"minor\",\"location\":\"packages/app/src/client/App.tsx:833\",\"issue\":\"The card alert indicator is now gated on a connected entry, so stale retained values are not presented as live alerts.\",\"suggestion\":\"No further change required.\",\"status\":\"resolved\"},{\"id\":\"F4\",\"severity\":\"nit\",\"location\":\"packages/common/src/alerts.ts:110\",\"issue\":\"The comparator now performs genuine set equality using unique-set sizes and membership, including for duplicate-containing inputs.\",\"suggestion\":\"No further change required.\",\"status\":\"resolved\"},{\"id\":\"F5\",\"severity\":\"nit\",\"location\":\"packages/agent/src/main.ts:193\",\"issue\":\"Both comments now accurately state that scan subscribes synchronously during construction and that the emitter is cleared on scan/source teardown.\",\"suggestion\":\"No further change required.\",\"status\":\"resolved\"}],\"responseToRebuttal\":\"F1: Conceded and resolved. The explicit settings control was a suggested implementation, not an independent requirement; the one-shot pointerdown/keydown path fixes the actual user-activation defect and has correct teardown. F2: Resolved; optional API absence remains a no-op while promise failures are contained. F3: Resolved; the connected-state gate aligns the card with the badge’s live-only semantics. F4: Resolved; the new predicate is true set equality. F5: Resolved; both lifecycle comments now match the pinned reactor implementation. I also accept the environment explanation: the prior full-suite EROFS failures were sandbox artifacts and the unchanged process-stream failure was not held as a finding.\"}"}}
